    {
        'id': 'NEW036',
        'category': 'Storage',
        'error_name': 'External Hard Drive Not Showing Up',
        'user_error_text': 'My external hard drive is not showing up',
        'symptoms': 'External drive not visible in File Explorer, no drive letter assigned, drive not detected',
        'cause': 'Power issues, cable problems, missing drive letter, offline drive, or driver issues',
        'step_1': '✅ Option 1: Check the External Drive & Cable (VERY IMPORTANT)\nDisconnect and reconnect the drive firmly\nTry a different USB cable\nTry a different USB port (rear ports on desktops)\nIf it has a separate power adapter, ensure it\'s plugged in\nTest the drive on another computer\n❌ Not detected → drive/cable likely faulty\n✔️ Detected → issue is on your PC\n📌 Power or cable issues are the most common cause.',
        'step_2': '✅ Option 2: Restart Your Computer\nRestart Windows\nPlug in the external drive after Windows fully loads\n✔️ Clears temporary USB and driver glitches.',
        'step_3': '✅ Option 3: Check Disk Management (CRITICAL STEP)\nPress Win + X → Disk Management\nLook for your external drive (even if no letter)\nPossible states & fixes:\nNo drive letter → Right-click → Change Drive Letter → Add\nOffline → Right-click → Online\nUnallocated → Right-click → New Simple Volume ⚠️ (formats drive – data loss)\nHealthy but not visible → Assign a letter\n📌 Many drives are detected but not assigned a letter.',
        'step_4': '✅ Option 4: Check Device Manager\nWin + X → Device Manager\nExpand Disk drives and Universal Serial Bus controllers\nLook for: External drive listed / Unknown device \nIf found: Right-click → Uninstall device\nRestart PC (driver reinstalls automatically)\n✔️ Fixes corrupted USB/storage drivers.',
        'step_5': '✅ Option 5: Disable USB Power Saving (MOST EFFECTIVE)\nDevice Manager → Universal Serial Bus controllers\nFor each USB Root Hub: Properties → Power Management\n❌ Uncheck Allow the computer to turn off…\nClick OK and restart\n📌 Prevents Windows from powering down external drives.',
        'verification': 'External drive should appear in File Explorer with a drive letter',
        'risk': 'low',
        'os_version': 'Windows 10/11',
        'device_type': 'Desktop/Laptop',
        'tag': 'external drive, hard drive, storage, usb drive',
        'log_snippet': ''
    },
    {
        'id': 'NEW037',
        'category': 'Storage',
        'error_name': 'Disk Write-Protected Error',
        'user_error_text': 'I am getting a disk write-protected error',
        'symptoms': 'Cannot write to USB drive or SD card, write-protected error message, cannot format or delete files',
        'cause': 'Physical write-protect switch, software write-protection, registry setting, or corrupted file system',
        'step_1': '✅ Option 1: Check for a Physical Write-Protect Switch (VERY IMPORTANT)\nLook at the USB flash drive / SD card\nSome devices have a small LOCK switch\nMove it to Unlock\nReinsert the drive and test again\n📌 This is the most common and easiest cause.',
        'step_2': '✅ Option 2: Restart PC & Reconnect the Drive\nSafely remove the drive\nRestart the computer\nPlug the drive back in after Windows fully loads\n✔️ Clears temporary protection flags.',
        'step_3': '✅ Option 3: Remove Write Protection Using DiskPart (MOST EFFECTIVE)\n⚠️ Follow carefully.\nPress Win + X → Terminal (Admin) or Command Prompt (Admin)\nType commands one by one: diskpart & list disk\nIdentify your USB disk number (check size)\nThen run:\nselect disk X [disk number]\nattributes disk clear readonly\nexit\n✔️ This removes software-level write protection.',
        'step_4': '✅ Option 4: Check Registry Write-Protection Setting\nPress Win + R → type regedit\nGo to: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Control\\StorageDevicePolicies\nOn the right: If WriteProtect exists → double-click → Set 0\nRestart PC\n📌 If the key doesn\'t exist, skip this step.',
        'step_5': '✅ Option 5: Format the Drive (⚠️ DATA LOSS)\nOnly do this if data is not important.\nRight-click drive → Format\nChoose: File system: exFAT or NTFS\nStart format\n❌ If format fails with write-protected error → hardware issue likely',
        'verification': 'Should be able to write, delete, and format files on the drive',
        'risk': 'medium',
        'os_version': 'Windows 10/11',
        'device_type': 'Desktop/Laptop',
        'tag': 'write protected, disk protection, usb protection, sd card',
        'log_snippet': ''
    },
    {
        'id': 'NEW038',
        'category': 'Storage',
        'error_name': 'File System Error Preventing Access',
        'user_error_text': 'A file system error is preventing access to my drive',
        'symptoms': 'Cannot access drive, file system error message, drive shows as RAW or unreadable, asks to format',
        'cause': 'Corrupted file system, connection issues, BitLocker encryption, permission problems, or failing drive',
        'step_1': '✅ Option 1: Restart the Computer (VERY IMPORTANT)\nRestart Windows once\nDo not force shutdown again\nTry opening the drive after restart\n📌 Minor file system glitches often clear after reboot.',
        'step_2': '✅ Option 2: Check Cables & Connection (External Drives)\nSafely remove the drive\nReconnect it firmly\nTry a different USB port\nTry a different cable\nAvoid USB hubs\n✔️ Poor connections can trigger file system errors.',
        'step_3': '✅ Option 3: Check for BitLocker Encryption\nOpen This PC\nIf the drive shows a lock icon: Right-click → Unlock\nEnter BitLocker password or recovery key\n📌 Encrypted drives will show file system errors if locked.',
        'step_4': '✅ Option 4: Check Permissions & Ownership\nRight-click drive → Properties\nSecurity tab → ensure your user has Full control\nIf access denied: Advanced → Change owner to your user account\n📌 Permission corruption can mimic file system errors.',
        'step_5': '✅ Option 5: RAW Drive or Still Inaccessible (CRITICAL)\nIf the drive shows:\nRAW\nFile system not recognized\nAsks to format\n❌ Do NOT format if you need the data.\n✔️ Safe options: Try another PC\nUse data recovery software\nConsult a professional data recovery service',
        'verification': 'Drive should be accessible and files should be readable',
        'risk': 'high',
        'os_version': 'Windows 10/11',
        'device_type': 'Desktop/Laptop',
        'tag': 'file system error, raw drive, inaccessible drive, corruption',
        'log_snippet': ''
    },
